606":"1606","1505":"1505","Ecclesgrieg Castle, Morphie, Kincardinshire, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Skotland","Gartreenick, Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"abt. 1508–May 1572":"circa 1508–mei 1572","1505–1546":"1505–1546","1536–1606":"1536–1606","1508–1572":"1508–1572","1536":"1536","1546":"1546","May 1572":"mei 1572","1572":"1572","1508":"1508","abt. 1508":"circa 1508","1606":"1606","1505":"1505","Ecclesgrieg Castle, Morphie, Kincardinshire, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Schotland","Gartreenick, Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"abt. 1508–May 1572":"about 1508–May 1572","1505–1546":"1505–1546","1536–1606":"1536–1606","1508–1572":"1508–1572","1536":"1536","1546":"1546","May 1572":"May 1572","1572":"1572","1508":"1508","abt. 1508":"about 1508","1606":"1606","1505":"1505","Ecclesgrieg Castle, Morphie, Kincardinshire, Scotland":"Kincardineshire, Scotland","Gartreenick, Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Graham was born about 1508, in Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Egidia Giles Douglas. He died in May 1572, at the age of 65."},"et":{"abt. 1508–May 1572":"umbes